li.p:
We construct the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ -1 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which shows that
\xvec=\threevec{-2x_3}{x_3}{x_3} = x_3\threevec{-2}{1}{1}\text{.}

There are many possibilities.  For instance,

  B = \left[\begin{array}{rr}
  -2 \amp 2 \\
  1 \amp -1 \\
  1 \amp -1 \\
  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

We compute that
SA = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 7 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ \end{array}\right] = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 14 \amp 0 \amp 14 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
To scale the third row by -3, we would use the matrix S= \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\ \end{array}\right] .

We compute that
PA = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ \end{array}\right] = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
To interchange the first and third rows, we would use P= \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right] .

Keeping track of the operations we perform in Gaussian elimination, we define
\begin{array}{cc} L_1= \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right], \amp L_2= \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right], \\ L_3 = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.} \end{array}
Then L_3L_2L_1A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp -4 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 8 \\ \end{array}\right] . So L=L_3L_2L_1 = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ -1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{array}\right] .

We find \bvec_1 and \bvec_2 by solving the
equations

  A\bvec_1=\twovec{1}{0}, A\bvec_2=\twovec{0}{1}\text{.}

This gives

  B = \left[
  \begin{array}{rr}
  -1 \amp -2 \\
  -2 \amp -3 \\
  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

 We have

	\begin{array}{rl}
	\xvec_2=A\xvec_1 = \amp A(c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2) \\
	=\amp c_1A\vvec_1 + c_2A\vvec_2 =
	c_1\vvec_1 +0.3c_2\vvec_2\text{.}
	\end{array}


  \begin{array}{rl}
\xvec_3=A\xvec_2=\amp A(c_1\vvec_1+0.3c_2\vvec_2) \\
= \amp c_1A\vvec_1 -0.3c_2A\vvec_2 =
c_1\vvec_1 +0.3^2c_2\vvec_2\text{.}
\end{array}

and so on.

After a very long time, the second term becomes
     increasingly close to zero and so
     \xvec\approx\frac{1000}{7}\vvec_1 = \twovec{5000/7}{2000/7}
     = \twovec{714.3}{285.7}\text{.}

 We have

	\begin{array}{rl}
	\xvec_2=A\xvec_1 = \amp A(c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2) \\
	=\amp c_1A\vvec_1 + c_2A\vvec_2 =
	c_1\vvec_1 +0.3c_2\vvec_2\text{.}
	\end{array}


  \begin{array}{rl}
\xvec_3=A\xvec_2=\amp A(c_1\vvec_1+0.3c_2\vvec_2) \\
= \amp c_1A\vvec_1 +0.3c_2A\vvec_2 =
c_1\vvec_1 +0.3^2c_2\vvec_2\text{.}
\end{array}

and so on.

After a very long time, the second term becomes
     increasingly close to zero and so
     \xvec\approx\frac{1000}{7}\vvec_1 = \twovec{5000/7}{2000/7}
     = \twovec{714.3}{285.7}\text{.}
